s a low-resolution image and then progressively refines it to higher resolutions.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe main challenge in generating high-resolution images using diffusion models is the introduction of semantic inaccuracies and object replication issues during the denoising process. Existing approaches, such as direct upsampling and diffusion-based super-resolution, have limitations in terms of image quality and efficiency. Potential solutions include developing more sophisticated truncate and relay strategies, combining diffusion models with other generative models, using advanced denoising techniques, and training models in a multi-resolution setting.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field:**\nDiffusion models have shown remarkable performance in various image generation tasks, but they struggle with generating high-resolution images with accurate semantics and fine details.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we generate high-resolution images using diffusion models while maintaining semantic accuracy and avoiding object replication issues?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nSolving this problem will significantly improve the quality of images generated by diffusion models, making them more suitable for applications that require high-resolution images. This will advance the field of generative models and have practical implications in areas such as image editing, consistent image sequence generation, and text-to-image generation.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nGenerating high-resolution images with accurate semantics and fine details is challenging due to the complex nature of the denoising process. Naive approaches, such as direct upsampling, can introduce artifacts and semantic inaccuracies. Advanced denoising techniques and sophisticated strategies are required to address these issues.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on improving the denoising process at a single resolution, but the transition between different resolutions remains a challenge. Existing methods, such as direct upsampling and diffusion-based super-resolution, have limitations in terms of image quality and efficiency. A more holistic approach that addresses the entire generation process is needed.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach involves developing a sophisticated truncate and relay strategy that can better handle the transition between different resolutions. This strategy will incorporate advanced denoising techniques and learned priors to ensure semantic accuracy and detail preservation. The method will be evaluated on a variety of datasets, and metrics such as FID, KID, CLIP-T, CIDEr, Meteor, and ROUGE will be used to assess the quality of the generated images. The expected outcomes include high-quality, semantically accurate high-resolution images with lower computational costs."}

