gher-resolution model will take over to refine the image details."\n\n2. **Advanced Noise Scheduling:**\n   - **Details:** Explain the machine learning approach for learning optimal noise schedules.\n   - **Example:** "A reinforcement learning algorithm will be used to dynamically adjust noise schedules based on the image resolution and content. The algorithm will be trained on a subset of the dataset to learn optimal noise levels for different stages of denoising."\n\n3. **Hierarchical Models:**\n   - **Details:** Describe the architecture and training process of the hierarchical models.\n   - **Example:** "A hierarchical denoising approach will be implemented using a series of diffusion models of varying resolutions. Lower-resolution models will provide semantic guidance to higher-resolution models, ensuring semantic coherence across different resolutions."\n\n4. **Transformer Architectures:**\n   - **Details:** Explain how Transformer architectures will be integrated into the denoising process.\n   - **Example:** "Transformer-based architectures will be used to refine semantic information generated during early denoising stages. The Transformer will be trained to capture long-range dependencies and improve semantic coherence in high-resolution images."\n\n#### Dataset Selection Criteria\n1. **Datasets:**\n   - **Details:** Specify the datasets to be used and justify their selection.\n   - **Example:** "The FFHQ dataset will be used for training and evaluation due to its high resolution and diverse set of high-quality images. The ImageNet and COCO datasets will also be considered for additional diversity."\n\n2. **Rationale:**\n   - **Details:** Provide the rationale behind choosing these datasets.\n   - **Example:** "These datasets are widely used in image generation research and provide a diverse range of high-resolution images, making them suitable for training and evaluating our proposed approach."\n\n#### Evaluation Metrics\n1. **Metrics:**\n   - **Details:** List the evaluation metrics and explain their relevance.\n   - **Example:** "Metrics such as FID, KID, CLIP-T, CIDEr, Meteor, and ROUGE will be used to assess the quality of generated images. These metrics will provide a comprehensive evaluation of image quality, semantic coherence, and content similarity."\n\n2. **Relevance:**\n   - **Details:** Explain why these metrics are relevant.\n   - **Example:** "FID and KID measure the similarity between generated and real images, while CLIP-T assesses the semantic similarity. CIDEr, Meteor, and ROUGE evaluate the quality of generated images in terms of content and coherence."\n\nBy refining the methodology, dataset selection criteria, and evaluation metrics, you will ensure that the research proposal is well-defined and feasible. This will set a strong foundation for the subsequent steps, including literature review, feasibility study, preliminary experiments, and drafting the research paper.'}, 'task_results': [{'agent1': 'Result from the model:\nResult from the function:{"success": true, "message": "Successfully completed session d9af747d-8438-42d4-97b9-8bd3effe36bf", "full_chat_history": "In Session d9af747d-8438-42d4-97b9-8bd3effe36bf \\nFrom agent1 to agent3: Dear agent3,\\n\\nI hope this email finds you well. I am currently working on a research proposal titled \'Enhancing Semantic Accuracy and Computational Efficiency of Diffusion Models for High-Resolution Image Generation.\' I would greatly appreciate your feedback on the proposal to ensure that it is clear, comprehensive, and well-structured.\\n\\nPlease find attached the draft of the proposal. I would be particularly interested in your thoughts on the following areas:\\n- Clarity and specificity of the research questions.\\n- Feasibility and detail of the proposed methodology.\\n- Relevance and appropriateness of the proposed metrics.\\n- Any suggestions for improvement or additional considerations.\\n\\nYour feedback is invaluable and will greatly contribute 